# Coding Discipline (Karpathy-extended)

## 1. Explicit Assumptions
State assumptions before writing code. If multiple interpretations exist and
consequence is >15min of work: ask. Present interpretations with options, don't
pick silently. Name what's unclear — don't infer forward.

## 2. Minimal Scope
Write minimum code that solves the stated problem. Nothing beyond what was asked.
No abstractions for single-use code. No future-proofing nobody requested.
Every changed line traces to the user's explicit request.
Out-of-scope issues: log to .ohc/notepad.md, do not fix.

## 3. Surgical Changes
Remove only what YOUR changes made unused. Don't remove pre-existing dead code.
Small logical commits. Each commit = one logical change.
Every changed line explainable from the commit message alone.

## 4. Goal-Driven Execution
Write explicit verifiable success criterion before any code.
"Tests pass" is not a criterion. "All 23 auth.test.ts cases pass with 0 skips" is.
Loop until criterion is met. Never claim done without verifying.

## OHC Extensions
- Workflow gate: >30min task → confirm plan in .ohc/plans/ exists first
- Team handoff: finish work → update .ohc/notepad.md for next developer
- Scope verification: after finishing → confirm changed files match task scope
